{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open a web browser and go to `https://git-scm.com/downloads`. You should see download options for Windows, macOS, and Linux.",
      "title": "Open the Git download page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the button for your operating system. The Git installer should start downloading; if it does not, click the manual download link shown on the page.",
      "title": "Download the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the downloaded Git installer file from your Downloads folder. On Windows it ends in `.exe`; on macOS it usually ends in `.dmg` or `.pkg`.",
      "title": "Open the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Yes**, **Open**, or **Allow** if your computer asks for permission. The Git setup window should appear after you approve it.",
      "title": "Approve the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** or **Continue** on each setup screen, keeping the default settings, until you reach the **Install** button.",
      "title": "Accept the defaults"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Install** and wait for the progress bar to finish. You should see a completion screen when Git has been installed.",
      "title": "Install Git"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Finish** or **Close** on the completion screen. The installer window should disappear.",
      "title": "Close the installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your terminal. On Windows, open **Git Bash** from the Start menu. On macOS, open **Terminal** from Applications > Utilities.",
      "title": "Open a terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see a version number, such as `git version 2.45.0`.",
      "title": "Check the Git version"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confirm the command printed a Git version. If you see “command not found,” close the terminal, open it again, and run `git --version` once more.",
      "title": "Verify the installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Pull onto a firm, level shoulder or parking area away from traffic. Stop the car straight. If you cannot get fully out of traffic, call roadside assistance instead.",
      "title": "Move to Safe Ground"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn on the hazard lights. You should see both dashboard turn indicators flashing at the same time.",
      "title": "Turn On Hazards"
    },
    {
      "text": "Shift to Park for an automatic, or 1st gear for a manual. The vehicle should not roll when you release the brake pedal slowly.",
      "title": "Secure the Transmission"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull the parking brake fully on. You should feel it lock or see the parking brake light on the dashboard.",
      "title": "Set the Parking Brake"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place a wheel chock, rock, or sturdy block behind and in front of the tire diagonally opposite the flat. The chocked tire should not move.",
      "title": "Chock the Opposite Wheel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the trunk or cargo area and take out the jack, lug wrench, and wheel lock key if your vehicle uses one. Set them beside the flat tire.",
      "title": "Gather the Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the hubcap or lug nut cover if it blocks the lug nuts. Use the flat end of the lug wrench if needed. You should see all lug nuts exposed.",
      "title": "Remove the Wheel Cover"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fit the lug wrench onto one lug nut and turn it counterclockwise about a half turn. The nut should break loose but stay on the stud.",
      "title": "Loosen One Lug Nut"
    },
    {
      "text": "Loosen each remaining lug nut counterclockwise about a half turn. Keep the tire on the ground while doing this so the wheel does not spin.",
      "title": "Loosen the Other Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the marked jack point nearest the flat tire, usually a notch or reinforced spot under the rocker panel. If unsure, check the owner’s manual.",
      "title": "Find the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the jack under the jack point and align its saddle with the reinforced notch or pad. The jack should stand straight on firm ground.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Crank or pump the jack until the flat tire is about 1 inch off the ground. Stop if the jack leans, sinks, or shifts, then lower and reposition it.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gently push the vehicle near the flat tire with one hand. It should stay steady on the jack. Do not crawl under the vehicle.",
      "title": "Check Stability"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn each loosened lug nut counterclockwise until it comes off. Place the nuts together in a pocket, cup, or safe spot so none roll away.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire at the 3 and 9 o’clock positions and pull it straight toward you. Rock it gently if stuck. The wheel should slide off the studs.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the flat tire flat on the ground away from traffic. The hub should be fully clear, with the vehicle still supported by the jack.",
      "title": "Set the Tire Aside"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place **30 g** of coarse coffee grounds in a bowl for one 12 oz cup. If you do not have a scale, use about **4 level tablespoons**. You should see an even, coarse pile.",
      "title": "Measure the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour **450 g** or **450 ml** of water into your kettle. If using cups, use just under **2 cups**. You should have enough water for one full mug.",
      "title": "Measure the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat the water to about **200°F**. If it boils, wait 30 seconds before using it. You should see steam, but the water should not be rolling hard.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the French press on a stable counter. Make sure the plunger is removed and the empty glass carafe is ready to fill.",
      "title": "Set Out the Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the measured grounds into the bottom of the French press. The grounds should form an even layer across the base.",
      "title": "Add the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the hot water over the grounds until the press is filled to your measured amount. All grounds should be wet and floating near the top.",
      "title": "Pour in the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start a timer for **4 minutes** as soon as the water is in. You should see the timer counting down or up from 0:00.",
      "title": "Start the Timer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gently stir the coffee once with a spoon after about 30 seconds. The dry clumps should break apart and the surface should look evenly wet.",
      "title": "Stir the Crust"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. The filter should rest just above the coffee surface.",
      "title": "Place the Lid"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait until the timer reaches **4 minutes**. The coffee should look darker, with most grounds settled below the surface.",
      "title": "Let It Brew"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the plunger straight down slowly until it reaches the bottom. Stop if you feel strong resistance, then continue gently.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your mug right away. The cup should look clear of large grounds, and the French press should be mostly empty.",
      "title": "Pour the Coffee"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Bring a garden fork or tiller, rake, compost, tomato or vegetable fertilizer, hose or watering can, and gloves to the bed. You should have everything within reach before you start.",
      "title": "Gather Your Supplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull weeds and remove rocks, old roots, sticks, and debris from the tomato bed. You should see mostly bare soil across the planting area.",
      "title": "Clear the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze a handful of soil. It should feel damp and crumble apart. If it is dusty, water lightly before digging; if it is sticky, wait until it dries.",
      "title": "Check Soil Moisture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push a garden fork 10 to 12 inches into the soil and rock it back. Repeat across the bed until the whole area is loosened.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the fork or rake to break large clods into smaller pieces. The bed is ready when the soil looks crumbly instead of chunky.",
      "title": "Break Up Clumps"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread 2 to 3 inches of finished compost over the entire bed. You should see an even dark layer covering the soil.",
      "title": "Spread Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle tomato or vegetable fertilizer over the compost using the amount on the label. Spread it evenly so there are no heavy piles.",
      "title": "Add Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the compost and fertilizer into the top 8 to 10 inches of soil with the fork. The soil should look evenly mixed, with compost throughout.",
      "title": "Mix in Amendments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rake the bed until the surface is smooth and level. Remove any new rocks or roots that appear as you rake.",
      "title": "Smooth the Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the bed slowly until the top several inches are evenly moist. Stop if water begins to puddle on the surface.",
      "title": "Moisten the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Leave the prepared bed undisturbed for 24 to 48 hours. The soil should settle slightly and stay crumbly, not crusted or soggy.",
      "title": "Let the Soil Settle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze one more handful of soil before planting. It should hold together briefly, then crumble when touched. If it does, the bed is ready for tomatoes.",
      "title": "Confirm Readiness"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your fabric, pillowcase pattern, tape measure or ruler, fabric scissors, straight pins, and fabric marker on a clear table. You should have enough space to lay the fabric flat.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the pillowcase pattern instructions to the cutting layout page. You should see the names, sizes, and quantities of each fabric piece to cut.",
      "title": "Open the Cutting Layout"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the pillowcase size you are making and circle or note that size on the pattern. Use only the cutting lines for that size.",
      "title": "Select Your Size"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the fabric on the table with the wrong side facing up. The fabric should be flat, with no bumps or twisted edges.",
      "title": "Lay Out the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold the fabric exactly as the pattern layout shows, usually with selvage edges together. The fold should be straight and smooth.",
      "title": "Fold the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure the first pattern piece or listed rectangle with your ruler. Confirm it matches the size shown in the pattern before cutting.",
      "title": "Measure the First Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the first pattern piece on the fabric in the spot shown on the layout. The printed label should face up and be easy to read.",
      "title": "Place the First Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Line up the grainline arrow on the pattern so it runs parallel to the fabric selvage. Measure both arrow ends to the selvage; they should match.",
      "title": "Align the Grainline"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert straight pins through the pattern and fabric, spacing them every few inches. The pattern should lie flat without shifting.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mark any dots, notches, or fold lines shown on the pattern with a fabric marker. You should see each mark clearly on the fabric.",
      "title": "Mark Pattern Symbols"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut along the pattern’s cutting line with fabric scissors. Keep the lower scissor blade on the table so the edge stays smooth.",
      "title": "Cut the First Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the pins and place the cut fabric piece beside the pattern piece. Keep the pattern label with it so you can identify it later.",
      "title": "Set Aside the Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Repeat the measuring, placing, aligning, pinning, marking, and cutting steps for each remaining pillowcase pattern piece.",
      "title": "Cut Remaining Pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compare your cut pieces with the pattern’s cutting list. You should have the correct number of pieces for the pillowcase before sewing.",
      "title": "Check the Piece Count"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open a clip-on, pedal, or phone tuner. If using a reference pitch, open notes for standard tuning: low E, A, D, G, B, high E.",
      "title": "Open Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the tuner to **Guitar** or **Chromatic** mode. If it asks for calibration, choose `440 Hz`. You should see a note name area and a tuning meter.",
      "title": "Set Standard Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold the guitar in playing position and mute every string except the thickest string. The tuner should react only when you play that string.",
      "title": "Mute Extra Strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `E` centered or green. With a reference pitch, match the low E sound closely.",
      "title": "Tune the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `A` centered or green. If using a reference pitch, match the A note.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `D` centered or green. If the needle is left, tighten; if right, loosen.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `G` centered or green. Let the note ring while you adjust.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `B` centered or green. Adjust slowly; this string changes pitch quickly.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows `E` centered or green. This is the high E string.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck each string from thickest to thinnest: `E A D G B E`. Each note should appear centered or green on the tuner.",
      "title": "Check All Strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retune any string that is not centered or green. Stop when all six strings read `E A D G B E` in order.",
      "title": "Finish the Tuning"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn the camera on and remove the lens cap. You should see the scene through the viewfinder or rear screen.",
      "title": "Turn On the Camera"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the mode dial to **M** for Manual. The screen should show ISO, aperture, and shutter speed values you can change.",
      "title": "Select Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO** button or open the Quick Menu, then set ISO to `100` outdoors or `400` indoors. The ISO value should update on the screen.",
      "title": "Set the ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the aperture dial to choose `f/4` for a blurred background or `f/8` for more of the scene sharp. Confirm the f-number changes on screen.",
      "title": "Set the Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Point the camera at your subject and frame the photo. Keep the main subject in the center while you set exposure.",
      "title": "Frame Your Scene"
    },
    {
      "text": "Half-press the shutter button to wake the light meter. You should see an exposure scale with a marker near `-`, `0`, or `+`.",
      "title": "Activate the Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial until the meter marker lines up with `0`. If the number gets too slow to handhold, stop around `1/125`.",
      "title": "Set Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button fully to take one test photo. The image should appear briefly on the rear screen.",
      "title": "Take a Test Photo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press **Playback**, then press **Info** or **Display** until the histogram appears. You should see a graph showing the photo’s brightness.",
      "title": "Check the Histogram"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the graph is crushed against the left edge, use a slower shutter speed, lower f-number, or higher ISO. Retake the photo after changing one setting.",
      "title": "Fix Underexposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the graph is crushed against the right edge, use a faster shutter speed, higher f-number, or lower ISO. Retake the photo after changing one setting.",
      "title": "Fix Overexposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Keep the settings when the photo looks natural and the histogram is not pressed hard against either edge. Your scene is properly exposed.",
      "title": "Confirm Proper Exposure"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand in front of a mirror or record yourself from the side. You should be able to see your whole body from feet to head.",
      "title": "Set Up Your View"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your feet about shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward, around 10–30 degrees. Your weight should feel even across both feet.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press your big toe, little toe, and heel into the floor on each foot. You should feel stable without your arches collapsing inward.",
      "title": "Anchor Your Feet"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand tall with your chest up and ribs stacked over your hips. Look straight ahead. Your spine should feel long, not rounded or overarched.",
      "title": "Stack Your Torso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extend both arms straight in front of your chest. Your arms should stay level and help you balance as you squat.",
      "title": "Raise Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tighten your midsection as if preparing for a gentle punch. You should feel firm around your waist while still being able to breathe.",
      "title": "Brace Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips slightly back to begin the squat. Your knees may bend, but your hips should move first instead of dropping straight down.",
      "title": "Start With Hips"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and lower your body slowly. Keep your heels down and your chest facing forward as your hips move toward the floor.",
      "title": "Lower With Control"
    },
    {
      "text": "Guide your knees in the same direction as your toes. In the mirror, your knees should not cave inward toward each other.",
      "title": "Track Your Knees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower until your thighs are about parallel to the floor, or stop earlier if your heels lift or your back rounds. Your position should still feel controlled.",
      "title": "Reach Your Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pause for one second at the bottom. Check that your heels are down, knees track over toes, chest stays up, and back stays neutral.",
      "title": "Check the Bottom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push the floor away through your whole foot to stand up. Your hips and chest should rise together without tipping forward.",
      "title": "Stand Back Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze your glutes lightly at the top and return to tall posture. Your knees and hips should be straight without leaning backward.",
      "title": "Finish Tall"
    },
    {
      "text": "Perform 5 slow squats using the same setup. After each rep, confirm your heels stay down, knees track with toes, and chest stays lifted.",
      "title": "Practice 5 Reps"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe farinha, líquido morno, fermento biológico, açúcar, sal e gordura conforme a receita. Deixe também uma tigela grande, colher e bancada limpas à mão.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aqueça a água ou o leite até ficar morno, entre 35 °C e 40 °C. Ao tocar, deve parecer confortável, não quente. Se estiver muito quente, espere esfriar.",
      "title": "Aqueça o líquido"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dissolva o fermento e o açúcar no líquido morno, em uma tigela pequena. Mexa até não ver grãos secos de fermento na superfície.",
      "title": "Dissolva o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deixe a mistura parada por 5 a 10 minutos. Ela deve formar espuma ou bolhas. Se nada acontecer, descarte e refaça com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a farinha em uma tigela grande e abra um espaço no centro com a colher. Você deve ver uma cavidade para receber os líquidos.",
      "title": "Prepare a farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Espalhe o sal nas bordas da farinha, longe do centro. O sal deve ficar misturado à farinha, sem tocar diretamente o fermento ativado.",
      "title": "Adicione o sal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje o fermento ativado no centro da farinha. A mistura deve cair na cavidade e manter a espuma visível por alguns segundos.",
      "title": "Junte o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque o óleo ou a manteiga derretida no centro da tigela, junto ao fermento. Use a quantidade indicada na receita.",
      "title": "Adicione a gordura"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mexa a massa com uma colher ou com as mãos até a farinha seca desaparecer. A massa deve ficar irregular, úmida e começar a desgrudar da tigela.",
      "title": "Misture a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aperte a massa com os dedos. Se estiver seca, adicione 1 colher de sopa de líquido; se grudar muito, polvilhe pouca farinha. Ela deve ficar macia e levemente pegajosa.",
      "title": "Ajuste a textura"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe uma camada fina de farinha sobre a bancada limpa. A superfície deve ficar coberta de leve, sem formar montes de farinha.",
      "title": "Enfarinhe a bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a massa sobre a bancada enfarinhada. Raspe a tigela com a mão ou espátula para aproveitar toda a massa.",
      "title": "Transfira a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Empurre a massa para frente com a base da mão, dobre ao meio e gire um quarto de volta. Repita esse movimento em ritmo constante.",
      "title": "Sove a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue sovando por 8 a 10 minutos. A massa deve ficar lisa, elástica e menos grudenta. Se grudar na bancada, polvilhe só um pouco de farinha.",
      "title": "Continue sovando"
    },
    {
      "text": "Estique um pedaço pequeno da massa entre os dedos. Ela deve abrir uma película fina antes de rasgar. Se rasgar rápido, sove por mais 2 minutos.",
      "title": "Teste a elasticidade"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola lisa, puxando as bordas para baixo. A superfície deve ficar esticada e uniforme, pronta para descansar e crescer.",
      "title": "Forme a bola"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Coloca llave ajustable, destornillador, pinzas, cinta de plomero, trapo y piezas de repuesto cerca del lavabo. Debes tener todo al alcance antes de abrir el grifo.",
      "title": "Reúne las herramientas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira las válvulas bajo el lavabo hacia la derecha hasta que se detengan. Si no hay válvulas, cierra la llave general de la casa.",
      "title": "Cierra el agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Levanta o gira la manija del grifo hasta la posición de abierto. Debe salir el agua restante y luego detenerse por completo.",
      "title": "Abre el grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón o trapo sobre el desagüe. Esto evita que tornillos pequeños caigan dentro del lavabo.",
      "title": "Tapa el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Levanta la tapa decorativa de la manija con un destornillador plano. Debes ver el tornillo que sujeta la manija.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira el tornillo de la manija hacia la izquierda hasta sacarlo. Déjalo en un lugar visible para no perderlo.",
      "title": "Quita el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tira de la manija hacia arriba o hacia afuera. Si está pegada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado hasta que salga.",
      "title": "Retira la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Afloja la tuerca de retención con la llave ajustable girándola hacia la izquierda. Debe quedar libre la pieza interna del grifo.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca"
    },
    {
      "text": "Saca el cartucho o vástago tirando recto hacia arriba. Colócalo sobre un trapo en el mismo orden en que salió.",
      "title": "Extrae la pieza interna"
    },
    {
      "text": "Revisa la arandela, los O-rings y el cartucho. Busca grietas, endurecimiento, deformación o desgaste visible.",
      "title": "Inspecciona las piezas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lleva la pieza dañada a la ferretería y pide una igual. Verifica que el tamaño y la forma coincidan antes de instalarla.",
      "title": "Consigue el repuesto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la arandela, O-ring o cartucho nuevo en la misma posición que la pieza anterior. Debe entrar firme, sin forzar.",
      "title": "Instala la pieza nueva"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vuelve a colocar la tuerca de retención y apriétala hacia la derecha. Detente cuando quede firme; no la aprietes en exceso.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la manija en su eje y aprieta el tornillo hacia la derecha. La manija debe moverse sin quedar floja.",
      "title": "Reinstala la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Presiona la tapa decorativa sobre la manija hasta que encaje. Debe quedar alineada y sin levantarse.",
      "title": "Coloca la tapa"
    },
    {
